<HEAD>With AM-Poll-US-Soviet, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   This <ORGANIZATION>Media General-Associated Press</ORGANIZATION> poll is
based on telephone interviews <DATE>April 29-May 8</DATE> with 1,204 adults in
the continental <LOCATION>United States</LOCATION>. The phone numbers were selected
randomly by computer and interviews were conducted with the adult
resident of each home who had the most recent birthday.
   The results were weighted to adjust for variations in the
sample. The poll has a three-point margin of error, meaning that
theoretically the results would be within <PERCENT>3 percentage points</PERCENT> of
the same 19 times out of 20 if every adult American were asked the
same questions. The error margin is larger for subgroups _ five
points for Republicans, for example, and nine points for
respondents who have done postgraduate work.
   There are other sources of potential error in polls, including
the wording and order of questions. These are the questions and
responses in this poll:
   1. Do you think the president of the <LOCATION>United States</LOCATION> and the
leader of the <LOCATION>Soviet Union</LOCATION> should meet at regular intervals even
without any major items on the agenda, or should they meet only to
complete major treaties?
   Regular intervals: <PERCENT>78 percent</PERCENT>. Major treaties: <PERCENT>16 percent</PERCENT>. Don't
know or no answer: <PERCENT>6 percent</PERCENT>.
   2. The <LOCATION>United States</LOCATION> and the Soviets recently agreed on a treaty
to abolish each country's medium-range nuclear weapons in <LOCATION>Europe</LOCATION>.
Do you think that will increase the chance of non-nuclear war in
<LOCATION>Europe</LOCATION>, decrease the chance of non-nuclear war in <LOCATION>Europe</LOCATION>, or won't
it make much of a difference?
   Increase: <PERCENT>11 percent</PERCENT>. Decrease: <PERCENT>26 percent</PERCENT>. Not much difference:
<PERCENT>55 percent</PERCENT>. Don't know or no answer: <PERCENT>8 percent</PERCENT>.
   3. Do you support or oppose the U.S.-Soviet treaty to eliminate
each country's medium-range nuclear weapons?
   Support: <PERCENT>73 percent</PERCENT>. Oppose: <PERCENT>15 percent</PERCENT>. Don't know, no answer:
<PERCENT>12 percent</PERCENT>.
   4. Would you support or oppose a U.S.-Soviet treaty to abolish
<PERCENT>50 percent</PERCENT> of each country's long-range nuclear weapons?
   Support: <PERCENT>73 percent</PERCENT>. Oppose: <PERCENT>15 percent</PERCENT>. Don't know or no
answer: <PERCENT>12 percent</PERCENT>.
   5. If the <LOCATION>United States</LOCATION> and the <LOCATION>Soviet Union</LOCATION> abolished all their
nuclear weapons, do you think that would increase the chance of
non-nuclear war, decrease it, or wouldn't it make much of a
difference?
   Increase, <PERCENT>22 percent</PERCENT>. Decrease, <PERCENT>30 percent</PERCENT>. Not much difference,
<PERCENT>40 percent</PERCENT>. Don't know or no answer: <PERCENT>8 percent</PERCENT>.
   6. <PERSON>Ronald Reagan</PERSON> has proposed the <ORGANIZATION>Strategic Defense Initiative</ORGANIZATION>,
known as <ORGANIZATION>Star Wars</ORGANIZATION>, as a missile defense system. Do you think the
<LOCATION>United States</LOCATION> should drop SDI in exchange for a Soviet agreement to
a big cut in nuclear weapons?
   Yes, <PERCENT>33 percent</PERCENT>. No, <PERCENT>49 percent</PERCENT>. Don't know or no answer, <PERCENT>18
percent</PERCENT>.
   7. Without an arms agreement with the Soviets, do you think work
on SDI should proceed as it is now, or should it be increased, or
reduced, or dropped?
   Proceed as now, <PERCENT>37 percent</PERCENT>. Increase, <PERCENT>19 percent</PERCENT>. Reduce, <PERCENT>13
percent</PERCENT>. Drop, <PERCENT>17 percent</PERCENT>. Don't know or no answer, <PERCENT>14 percent</PERCENT>.
   8. Which country do you think has more political influence in
the world right now _ the <LOCATION>United States</LOCATION>, or the <LOCATION>Soviet Union</LOCATION>, or
are they about equal?
   <LOCATION>United States</LOCATION>, <PERCENT>41 percent</PERCENT>. <LOCATION>Soviet Union</LOCATION>, <PERCENT>14 percent</PERCENT>. About
equal, <PERCENT>38 percent</PERCENT>. Don't know or no answer, <PERCENT>7 percent</PERCENT>.
   9. Which country do you think is stronger militarily right now _
the <LOCATION>United States</LOCATION>, or the <LOCATION>Soviet Union</LOCATION>, or are they about equal?
   <LOCATION>United States</LOCATION> <PERCENT>28 percent</PERCENT>. <LOCATION>Soviet Union</LOCATION> <PERCENT>33 percent</PERCENT>. About equal
<PERCENT>29 percent</PERCENT>. Don't know or no answer, <PERCENT>10 percent</PERCENT>.
   10. Overall, do you have a favorable or unfavorable opinion of
Soviet leader <PERSON>Mikhail Gorbachev</PERSON>?
   Favorable, <PERCENT>54 percent</PERCENT>. Unfavorable, <PERCENT>20 percent</PERCENT>. Don't know or no
answer, <PERCENT>26 percent</PERCENT>.
   11. Overall, do you have a favorable or unfavorable opinion of
President <PERSON>Reagan</PERSON>?
   Favorable, <PERCENT>59 percent</PERCENT>. Unfavorable, <PERCENT>31 percent</PERCENT>. Don't know or no
answer, <PERCENT>10 percent</PERCENT>.
   12. Do you approve or disapprove of the way President <PERSON>Reagan</PERSON> is
handling relations with the <LOCATION>Soviet Union</LOCATION>?
   Approve, <PERCENT>71 percent</PERCENT>. Disapprove, <PERCENT>17 percent</PERCENT>. Don't know or no
answer, <PERCENT>12 percent</PERCENT>.
   13. Do you think the Soviets can be trusted to live up to their
arms control agreements?
   Yes, <PERCENT>24 percent</PERCENT>. No, <PERCENT>61 percent</PERCENT>. Don't know or no answer, <PERCENT>15
percent</PERCENT>.
</TEXT>
