<HEAD>Reporters' Notebook: With Reagan at the Waldorf</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By W. DALE NELSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   For President <PERSON>Reagan</PERSON>, his trip to <LOCATION>New York</LOCATION> for
the <ORGANIZATION>United Nations General Assembly</ORGANIZATION> meant a dramatic farewell
appearance. For fellow guests at his hotel, it meant something of a
nuisance.
   For reporters and photographers, it meant scrambling up and down
stairwells, waiting in line in a hotel kitchen and getting stuck in
an elevator.
   Reagan spoke at the <ORGANIZATION>U.N.</ORGANIZATION> on <DATE>Monday</DATE>, making his seventh
appearance there and his last before he leaves office in <DATE>January</DATE>.
   After his speech, he went to the <LOCATION>United States Mission</LOCATION> to the
<ORGANIZATION>United Nations</ORGANIZATION> for lunch. It's just across the street, so most
people would walk. Presidential security, however, required that he
make the crossing by motorcade.
</TEXT>
