<HEAD>Chinese Students Upset With Senate's Failure to Override Veto</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Bush-China, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DANA KENNEDY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Chinese students said they feared being shipped
back to their homeland after the <ORGANIZATION>Senate</ORGANIZATION> upheld President <PERSON>Bush</PERSON>'s
veto of a bill protecting them from deportation when their visas
expire.
   ``Many students fear they will be sent back. I'm scared for all
my friends,'' said <PERSON>Yuan Liu</PERSON>, 30, a Chinese student enrolled at
<ORGANIZATION>Brandeis University</ORGANIZATION>.
   ``I think it's a sad day for us,'' said <PERSON>Pei Min Xin</PERSON>, 33, a
doctoral student at <ORGANIZATION>Harvard University</ORGANIZATION> who led the pro-democracy
protests in <LOCATION>Beijing</LOCATION> <DATE>last spring</DATE>. ``I'm afraid that the president
will continue his policy of accommodating the Chinese dictators.''
   <PERSON>Bush</PERSON> said the bill to eliminate that requirement was unnecessary
because he has signed an administrative order allowing Chinese
students to stay in the <LOCATION>United States</LOCATION>.
   The president said the legislation could have damaged <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION>
relations with <LOCATION>China</LOCATION>, which has condemned the action and threatened
to curtail exchange programs if it becomes law.
   The <ORGANIZATION>Senate</ORGANIZATION> voted 62-37 <DATE>Thursday</DATE> to override the presidential
veto, four votes short of the two-thirds necessary. The <ORGANIZATION>House</ORGANIZATION> voted
overwhelmingly <DATE>Wednesday</DATE> to reject <PERSON>Bush</PERSON>'s veto.
   Xiaxia Gong, 33, a <ORGANIZATION>Harvard</ORGANIZATION> graduate student, was among several
Chinese students gathered at the <ORGANIZATION>China Information Center</ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION>Newton</LOCATION>
who said the failed legislation would have given them a sense of
security.
   Many of the students fled to the <LOCATION>United States</LOCATION> after the Chinese
government cracked down on the protests in <LOCATION>Tiananmen Square</LOCATION>. Under
the visa's requirements, bearers must return to <LOCATION>China</LOCATION> when their
visas expire and live there for two years before they can apply for
a new one.
   The students fear that the president's order could be reversed
someday, leaving them vulnerable to deportation to their homeland
where they might be jailed.
   ``I don't believe <PERSON>Mr. Bush</PERSON>,'' <PERSON>Gong</PERSON> said. ``How can we believe
someone who has already cheated and sent high-level officials to
<LOCATION>China</LOCATION> when he said he would not? We don't want our destiny put in
someone else's hands.''
   In Salem, <LOCATION>Ore.</LOCATION>, Chinese students at <ORGANIZATION>Oregon State University</ORGANIZATION> said
they couldn't understand the <ORGANIZATION>Senate</ORGANIZATION> vote.
   ``It did send a message to <LOCATION>China</LOCATION>, but it did not stand for human
rights,'' <PERSON>Wang De Qian</PERSON>, co-vice president of the university's
Chinese student association.
   Shu <PERSON>Ouang</PERSON> said the student association ``did not want to
override the president, but the veto. We want to send a stronger
message to the Chinese butchers.''
</TEXT>
