<NOTE>$adv01</NOTE>
<NOTE>For release Saturday, Oct. 1</NOTE>
<HEAD>Today in History</HEAD>
<HEAD>By The Associated Press</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Today is <DATE>Saturday</DATE>, <DATE>Oct. 1</DATE>, the 275th day of <DATE>1988</DATE>. There are 91
days left in the year.
   Today's highlight in history:
   In <DATE>1908</DATE>, <ORGANIZATION>Henry Ford</ORGANIZATION> introduced the Model T to the market, at a
cost of <MONEY>$825</MONEY> per car. (In his book ``Ford: The Men and the
Machine,'' <PERSON>Robert Lacey</PERSON> points out that in <DATE>1908</DATE>, an average
teacher's annual salary was <MONEY>$850</MONEY>.) The Model T proved a huge
success; more than 15 million were sold before the line was
discontinued.
   On this date:
   In <DATE>1800</DATE>, <LOCATION>Spain</LOCATION> ceded <LOCATION>Louisiana</LOCATION> to <LOCATION>France</LOCATION> in a secret treaty.
   In <DATE>1885</DATE>, special delivery mail service began in the <LOCATION>United
States</LOCATION>.
   In <DATE>1903</DATE>, the <ORGANIZATION>Pittsburgh Pirates</ORGANIZATION> defeated the home team <LOCATION>Boston</LOCATION>
Pilgrims (Red Sox), 7-3, in the first World Series game. <LOCATION>Boston</LOCATION>,
however, went on to win the series, five games to three.
   In <DATE>1936</DATE>, Gen. <PERSON>Francisco Franco</PERSON> was proclaimed the head of an
insurgent Spanish state.
   In <DATE>1943</DATE>, Allied forces captured <LOCATION>Naples</LOCATION> during World War II.
   In <DATE>1949</DATE>, <ORGANIZATION>Communist Party</ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON>Mao Tse-tung</PERSON> raised the first
flag of the People's Republic of <LOCATION>China</LOCATION> in a proclamation ceremony
in Peking.
   In <DATE>1961</DATE>, <PERSON>Roger Maris</PERSON> hit his 61st home run during a 162-game
season, in comparison to <LOCATION>Babe Ruth</LOCATION>'s 60 home runs during a 154-game
season.
   In <DATE>1962</DATE>, <PERSON>Johnny Carson</PERSON> succeeded <PERSON>Jack Parr</PERSON> as permanent host of
<ORGANIZATION>NBC-TV</ORGANIZATION>'s ``Tonight'' show. Carson's guests that night were <PERSON>Joan
Crawford</PERSON>, <PERSON>Mel Brooks</PERSON>, <PERSON>Rudy Vallee</PERSON> and <PERSON>Tony Bennett</PERSON>.
   In <DATE>1971</DATE>, <ORGANIZATION>Walt Disney World</ORGANIZATION> opened in <LOCATION>Orlando</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Fla</LOCATION>.
   In <DATE>1980</DATE>, Soviet cosmonauts <PERSON>Valery Ryumin</PERSON> and <PERSON>Leonid Popov</PERSON> set a
world space endurance record as they spent their 176th day aboard
an orbiting Salyut space station.
   In <DATE>1982</DATE>, <LOCATION>West Germany</LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION>Parliament</ORGANIZATION> voted to oust <PERSON>Helmut Schmidt</PERSON>
as chancellor and replace him with <PERSON>Helmut Kohl</PERSON> _ the first time in
the federal republic's 33-year history that a chancellor was
removed by <ORGANIZATION>Parliament</ORGANIZATION>.
   In <DATE>1986</DATE>, former President <PERSON>Jimmy Carter</PERSON>'s new presidential
library and museum were dedicated in <LOCATION>Atlanta</LOCATION> with help from
President <PERSON>Reagan</PERSON>, who said he and his predecessor had come together
in ``mutual respect.''
   Ten years ago: <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> and Soviet negotiators concluded talks in
<LOCATION>Washington</LOCATION> on a strategic arms accord, saying that while remaining
issues remained unresolved, progress had been made.
   Five years ago: Former Vice President <PERSON>Walter F. Mondale</PERSON> won a
straw poll at the <LOCATION>Maine</LOCATION> Democratic state convention in <LOCATION>Augusta</LOCATION>,
thereby protecting his lead in his party's presidential race.
   One year ago: At least six people were killed when an earthquake
measuring 6.1 on the Richter scale struck the <LOCATION>Greater Los Angeles</LOCATION>
area.
   Today's birthdays: Pianist <PERSON>Vladimir Horowitz</PERSON> is 83. Actor <PERSON>Walter
Matthau</PERSON> is 67. Actor <PERSON>James Whitmore</PERSON> is 66. Former President <PERSON>Jimmy
Carter</PERSON> is 63. <PERSON>William Rehnquist</PERSON>, chief justice of the <LOCATION>United
States</LOCATION>, is 63. Actor <PERSON>Tom Bosley</PERSON> is 60. Actor <PERSON>George Peppard</PERSON> is 59.
Actor <PERSON>Richard Harris</PERSON> is 54. Actress-singer <PERSON>Julie Andrews</PERSON> is 52.
Former baseball player <PERSON>Rod Carew</PERSON> is 42.
   Thought for today: ``History is bunk!'' _ Attributed to <ORGANIZATION>Henry
Ford</ORGANIZATION>.
</TEXT>
