<H3> <TI>   Daily Views U.S. `Helplessness' Over PRC Policy </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Daily Views U.S. `Helplessness' Over PRC Policy </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU3005193594 Duesseldorf HANDELSBLATT in German 30 May 94 p 2 </F>
<F P=103> AU3005193594 </F>
<F P=104>  Duesseldorf HANDELSBLATT </F>
<F P=105>  German </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<FP=106> [Commentary by <PERSON>Peter Seidlitz</PERSON>: "Triumph of the Realists"] </F>
  [Text] President <PERSON>Bill Clinton</PERSON>'s decision to renew the 
most-favored-nation [MFN] clause will have a favorable effect on 
trade and cooperation between the <LOCATION>United States</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>China</LOCATION>. This 
is the gist of a statement published by the <ORGANIZATION>Chinese Government</ORGANIZATION> 
in <LOCATION>Beijing</LOCATION> as a reaction. 
  The business-like statement does not reflect the overt 
triumph the <ORGANIZATION>Chinese Government</ORGANIZATION> feels. A few days before the 
fifth anniversary of the clearing of <LOCATION>Tienanmen Square</LOCATION>, which 
claimed at least several hundred if not thousands of lives on 4 
<DATE>June 1989</DATE>, the <LOCATION>United States</LOCATION> has now also joined those who 
follow the popular slogan of "business first." The Europeans 
assumed such a pragmatic position a long time ago. <PERSON>Li Peng</PERSON>, 
<LOCATION>China</LOCATION>'s head of government who held his own with his tough 
course in <DATE>1989</DATE>, forcing reform-minded <ORGANIZATION>CPC</ORGANIZATION> head <PERSON>Zhao Zhiang</PERSON> into 
political exile, is expected on official visits in <LOCATION>Austria</LOCATION>, 
<LOCATION>Germany</LOCATION>, and <LOCATION>Romania</LOCATION>. That is realpolitik. 
  President <PERSON>Clinton</PERSON> decided that trade and human rights would 
henceforth be separated. This ends the annual tug-of-war about 
the renewal of tariff privileges. One year ago, the same 
President still linked the two issues and explicitly made the 
granting of preferential trade treatment dependent on an 
improvement of the human rights situation in <LOCATION>China</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>Tibet</LOCATION>. 
  Under the pressure of <ORGANIZATION>Big Business</ORGANIZATION>, the <LOCATION>United States</LOCATION> has 
now 
backed out and admitted its helplessness. After all, if the 
<LOCATION>West</LOCATION> is not even able to intervene in the cruel massacres in 
<LOCATION>Africa</LOCATION> and the <LOCATION>Balkans</LOCATION>, exerting pressure on <LOCATION>China</LOCATION>, which is 
bursting with strength, is absolutely impossible. 
  The renewal of the tariff privileges means that Chinese 
consumer goods -- such as shoes, clothes, toys, electronic 
equipment -- remain cheap in the <LOCATION>United States</LOCATION>. The <LOCATION>United 
States</LOCATION> is <LOCATION>China</LOCATION>'s biggest market. Products worth <MONEY>$33 billion</MONEY> go 
from <LOCATION>China</LOCATION> to the <LOCATION>United States</LOCATION>. Investments and trade are 
helping <LOCATION>China</LOCATION> to modernize the country. In the best case, this 
will in time lead to political transformation. There is no 
alternative. Nobody can wish for political chaos in the 
overpopulated country. 
  Reversely, <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> and multinational concerns, the <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> service 
sector enterprises such as banks and bond houses, and even 
fastfood restaurants such as <ORGANIZATION>McDonald's</ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION>Kentucky Fried Chicken</ORGANIZATION>, 
<ORGANIZATION>Pizza Hut</ORGANIZATION>, and <PERSON>Burger King</PERSON>, are now hoping for big business. So 
far, as with <LOCATION>Japan</LOCATION>, the <LOCATION>United States</LOCATION> has had a huge trade 
balance deficit with <LOCATION>China</LOCATION>. The <LOCATION>United States</LOCATION> only sells 
products worth <MONEY>$8 million</MONEY> to <LOCATION>China</LOCATION>. According to reports, <LOCATION>China</LOCATION> 
is said to order 50 <ORGANIZATION>Boeing</ORGANIZATION> aircraft in a single mammoth order 
worth <MONEY>$5 billion</MONEY> in return, so to speak, for granting the tariff 
privileges. The resumption of military contacts with the 
objective of armament sales has also been initiated. 
  The <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> business world is, therefore, satisfied with 
President <PERSON>Clinton</PERSON>'s decision. And <LOCATION>Hong Kong</LOCATION> rejoices, too. 
After all, the bulk of exports to <LOCATION>China</LOCATION> is shipped through this 
city, which will be a British colony until <DATE>1997</DATE>. <LOCATION>Hong Kong</LOCATION> 
would have lost enormous transactions. After this political 
U-turn, the Americans argue that changes or an easing of the 
politically tense situation would be achieved through economic 
relations rather than through political pressure. The slogan is 
change through business. 

</TEXT>

