<HEAD>Group Of 7 To Act Against Terrorists, Help Debtor Nations</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The leading industrial democracies plan to
take joint steps against terrorism and to assist Third World debtor
nations at their eocnomic summit next week in <LOCATION>Toronto</LOCATION>.
   Exercising the ``no-place-to-hide'' doctrine, the <LOCATION>United States</LOCATION>
and its six partners are expected to call on nations worldwide to
deny refueling to airplane hijackers, Secretary of State <PERSON>George P.
Shultz</PERSON> said <DATE>Wednesday</DATE>.
   The idea is to prevent hostage-holders from taking off with
their victims, <PERSON>Shultz</PERSON> said in a <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> Information Agency telecast
and at a <ORGANIZATION>White House</ORGANIZATION> news conference.
   ``It's a specific thing that if given broad endorsement might be
helpful,'' he said.
   <PERSON>Shultz</PERSON> said joint action at past economic summit meetings had
helped send terrorism into a decline in <LOCATION>Western Europe</LOCATION>, although he
said there also were indications it might be on the rise elsewhere.
   Sharing the <ORGANIZATION>White House</ORGANIZATION> platform with <PERSON>Shultz</PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION>Treasury</ORGANIZATION> Secretary
<PERSON>James A. Baker III</PERSON> predicted ``there's going to be real action on
economic issues,'' including decisions to ease the debt burden of
sub-Saharan African nations.
   Also, <PERSON>Baker</PERSON> said President <PERSON>Reagan</PERSON> and the leaders of <LOCATION>Canada</LOCATION>,
<LOCATION>Britain</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>France</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Italy</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Japan</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>West Germany</LOCATION> would consider
cooperative measures to prevent drug dealers from laundering their
profits through legitimate banks and ways for governments to share
intelligence information on narcotics.
   On another front, however, <PERSON>Shultz</PERSON> indicated the <LOCATION>United States</LOCATION>
would resist any attempt to impose stiffer economic sanctions
against <LOCATION>South Africa</LOCATION> because of its racial policies.
