<HEAD>Ortega Says Oliver North Was `Scapegoat'</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-North Trial, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY BETH SHERIDAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nicaraguan President <PERSON>Daniel Ortega</PERSON> said <DATE>Friday</DATE> that
<PERSON>Oliver North</PERSON> was the ``scapegoat'' for crimes committed by the <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION>
government and the person who really should be tried is former
President <PERSON>Reagan</PERSON>.
   North was convicted <DATE>Thursday</DATE> of three felony counts in
connection with the Iran-Contra case, which shadowed the <DATE>last two
years</DATE> of the <PERSON>Reagan</PERSON> administration.
   Ortega, on a swing through <LOCATION>Western Europe</LOCATION>, also told a news
conference that he hoped to improve relations with <LOCATION>Washington</LOCATION>.
   ``<PERSON>Oliver North</PERSON> has become the scapegoat for the crimes committed
by the government of the <LOCATION>United States</LOCATION> against <LOCATION>Nicaragua</LOCATION>,'' <PERSON>Ortega</PERSON>
said.
   ``But who was behind the actions of <PERSON>Oliver North</PERSON>? Who was the
boss of <PERSON>Oliver North</PERSON>? Who promoted the policy followed by <PERSON>Oliver
North</PERSON>? He's called <PERSON>Ronald Reagan</PERSON>. The person who ought to be
standing in the dock is <PERSON>Ronald Reagan</PERSON>, not <PERSON>Oliver North</PERSON>.
   Ortega also said President <PERSON>Bush</PERSON> ``seems clearly to have been
mixed up in these crimes.''
   He said his government had ``hopes and optimism'' that the
<LOCATION>United States</LOCATION> would change its policies toward <LOCATION>Nicaragua</LOCATION>.
<LOCATION>Washington</LOCATION> has maintained an economic embargo against the country
in addition to backing the Contras.
   Ortega is on a 10-nation tour to win economic aid for his
country's battered economy and to enlist Western European help in
persuading the <LOCATION>United States</LOCATION> to normalize relations with <LOCATION>Nicaragua</LOCATION>.
   He avoided questions about whether he had received promises of
aid from the countries he has visited thus far: <LOCATION>Italy</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Greece</LOCATION>,
<LOCATION>Norway</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Sweden</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Belgium</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Spain</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>France</LOCATION>.
</TEXT>
