<HEAD>Residents Of Conservative County Like Gorbachev More Than Bush</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 5 grafs to recast, include survey question on world
leaders; Picks up 6th graf, `The message ...'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviet leader <PERSON>Mikhail Gorbachev</PERSON> edged
President <PERSON>Bush</PERSON> in a survey of opinions toward world leaders in
Republican-dominated Orange County, but both ran behind British
Prime Minister <PERSON>Margaret Thatcher</PERSON> and President <PERSON>Reagan</PERSON>, according to
a poll released <DATE>today</DATE>.
   The <LOCATION>Los Angeles</LOCATION> Times-sponsored survey of <LOCATION>Orange County</LOCATION> residents
also revealed that <PERCENT>45 percent</PERCENT> think the Cold War between the
superpowers is coming to an end.
   The results came in the county that gave <PERSON>Bush</PERSON> and former
President <PERSON>Ronald Reagan</PERSON> their largest margins of victory of any <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION>
county in the presidential elections of <DATE>1980</DATE>, <DATE>1984</DATE> and <DATE>1988</DATE>.
   Asked, ``Do you have a favorable or unfavorable opinion of these
world leaders,'' positive ratings were as follows: <PERCENT>79 percent</PERCENT> for
<PERSON>Mrs. Thatcher</PERSON>, <PERCENT>76 percent</PERCENT> for <PERSON>Reagan</PERSON>, <PERCENT>70 percent</PERCENT> for <PERSON>Gorbachev</PERSON>, <PERCENT>67
percent</PERCENT> for <PERSON>Bush</PERSON> and <PERCENT>21 percent</PERCENT> for Israeli Prime Minister <PERSON>Yitzhak
Shamir</PERSON>.
   The poll, which involved 600 adults in the county southeast of
<LOCATION>Los Angeles</LOCATION>, had a <PERCENT>4 percentage point</PERCENT> margin of error, the newspaper
said.
   ``The message is that <LOCATION>Orange County</LOCATION> is more in the mainstream of
American thinking than the perception,'' said longtime <PERSON>Reagan</PERSON>
adviser <PERSON>Stu Spencer</PERSON>. ``Thinking on the Cold War undoubtedly is
changing due to <PERSON>Ronald Reagan</PERSON>'s policies.''
   The poll, taken <DATE>Jan. 13-17</DATE> by <ORGANIZATION>Mark Baldassare &amp; Associates</ORGANIZATION> of
<LOCATION>Irvine</LOCATION>, also found that more Orange County residents see <LOCATION>Japan</LOCATION> and
the Third World as a threat to the <LOCATION>United States</LOCATION> than the <LOCATION>Soviet
Union</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>China</LOCATION>.
   Thirty-one percent said the <ORGANIZATION>Third World</ORGANIZATION> presented the greatest
threat to the future of the <LOCATION>United States</LOCATION>. Just <PERCENT>17 percent</PERCENT> said the
<LOCATION>Soviet Union</LOCATION> presents the greatest threat, while <PERCENT>6 percent</PERCENT> felt
<LOCATION>China</LOCATION> was the greatest threat.
   On the issues of abortion, AIDS education and pornography, <LOCATION>Orange
County</LOCATION> residents again showed a softening of their perceived
conservative tendencies.
   Sixty percent opposed a <ORGANIZATION>Supreme Court</ORGANIZATION> ban on abortions and <PERCENT>56
percent</PERCENT> opposed a ban on the rental of X-rated films at video stores.
   Regarding acquired immune deficiency syndrome, <PERCENT>82 percent</PERCENT> favored
teaching youngsters in public schools about the use of condoms as a
means of controlling the spread of the deadly AIDS virus.
</TEXT>
