<HEAD>Poles In North America Choose Walesa</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Poland, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   <PERSON>Lech Walesa</PERSON> faces a runoff in <LOCATION>Poland</LOCATION>'s
presidential contest, but if it were up to the 36,000 Poles who
cast ballots in <LOCATION>North America</LOCATION> he'd already be in office.
   ``He is the only man for the job,'' <LOCATION>St. Louis</LOCATION> cab driver
<PERSON>Alexander Gorka</PERSON> said <DATE>Sunday</DATE>. ``He can take the country out of the
critical situation it's in.''
   Walesa, the Solidarity leader who led the revolt against four
decades of Communist rule in <LOCATION>Poland</LOCATION>, got <PERCENT>60 percent</PERCENT> of the vote
among Poles in <LOCATION>Canada</LOCATION> and the <LOCATION>United States</LOCATION> who voted <DATE>Saturday</DATE>,
said Consul <PERSON>Andrezj Jaroszynski</PERSON> in <LOCATION>Chicago</LOCATION>.
   Citing unofficial figures, he said Prime Minister <PERSON>Tadeusz
Mazowiecki</PERSON> placed second with <PERCENT>33 percent</PERCENT> of the ballots cast by
36,006 voters in <LOCATION>North America</LOCATION>.
   Upstart emigre businessman <PERSON>Stanislaw Tyminski</PERSON>, who beat
<PERSON>Mazowiecki</PERSON> for second in voting in <LOCATION>Poland</LOCATION>, had about <PERCENT>3 percent</PERCENT> of
the North American vote.
   In <LOCATION>Poland</LOCATION>, <PERSON>Walesa</PERSON> had just under <PERCENT>40 percent</PERCENT> of the vote with 44
of 49 provinces reporting. Tyminski, with <PERCENT>23 percent</PERCENT>, made a
surprise showing by beating <PERSON>Mazowiecki</PERSON>, who had <PERCENT>16 percent</PERCENT> of the
vote. Three other candidates trailed far behind. Final results were
expected later today.
   A <DATE>Dec. 9</DATE> runoff will be held between the two top vote-getters if
neither wins an outright majority.
   <PERSON>Gorka</PERSON>, who drove from <LOCATION>St. Louis</LOCATION> to the <ORGANIZATION>Polish Consulate</ORGANIZATION> in
<LOCATION>Chicago</LOCATION> to vote, said he cried when he cast his ballot for <PERSON>Walesa</PERSON>,
who had been favored to win.
   ``It was such an important day for me,'' <PERSON>Gorka</PERSON> said. ``It was
the first time in my life I had the freedom to vote in a truly
democratic election in <LOCATION>Poland</LOCATION>.''
   Turnout was lower than expected in <LOCATION>Chicago</LOCATION>, where only 9,810 of
more than 40,000 eligible voters went to three polling places,
<PERSON>Jaroszynski</PERSON> said.
   The metropolitan area has a larger bloc of Poles and
Polish-Americans, a total of 800,000 to 1.2 million, than any
municipality outside <LOCATION>Warsaw</LOCATION>.
   More than 16,000 ballots were cast in <LOCATION>New York state</LOCATION>, according
to the consulate in <LOCATION>New York City</LOCATION>.
   <PERSON>Alderman Roman C. Pucinski</PERSON>, a Walesa supporter, said returns in
<LOCATION>Chicago</LOCATION>, especially in the heavily Polish 41st ward he represents,
show <PERSON>Walesa</PERSON> ``does get his strength from the blue collar workers.''
   In <LOCATION>Chicago</LOCATION>, <PERSON>Walesa</PERSON> got <PERCENT>76 percent</PERCENT> of the vote to <PERSON>Mazowiecki</PERSON>'s <PERCENT>18
percent</PERCENT>.
   Unofficial North American results showed <PERSON>Walesa</PERSON> with 21,608, or
<PERCENT>60 percent</PERCENT>; <PERSON>Mazowiecki</PERSON> with 11,823, or <PERCENT>33 percent</PERCENT>; <PERSON>Tyminski</PERSON> with
1,238, or <PERCENT>3 percent</PERCENT>; and the remainder for the other three
candidates, <PERSON>Jaroszynski</PERSON> said.
   <LOCATION>Poland</LOCATION> allows naturalized <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> citizens to hold Polish passports
and vote. Newly arrived immigrants and visitors to the <LOCATION>United
States</LOCATION> also could vote. Balloting was at sites in <LOCATION>North America</LOCATION> on
<DATE>Saturday</DATE>; voting by mail was not permitted.
</TEXT>
