<HEAD>Today In History</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Today is <DATE>Sunday</DATE>, <DATE>October 8</DATE>, the 281st day of <DATE>1989</DATE>. There are 84
days left in the year. Yom Kippur, the <ORGANIZATION>Jewish Day of Atonement</ORGANIZATION>,
begins at sunset.
   Today's highlight in history:
   On <DATE>October 8, 1871</DATE>, one of <LOCATION>America</LOCATION>'s worst urban fires and
forest fires broke out in <LOCATION>Chicago</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>Peshtigo</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Wisc</LOCATION>. The <LOCATION>Chicago</LOCATION>
fire claimed more than 200 lives and destroyed more than 17,000
buildings. The <LOCATION>Wisconsin</LOCATION> blaze claimed an estimated 1,500 lives and
scorched 1.28 million acres of timberland.
   On this date:
   In <DATE>1869</DATE>, the 14th president of the <LOCATION>United States</LOCATION>, <PERSON>Franklin
Pierce</PERSON>, died in <LOCATION>Concord</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>N.H.</LOCATION>
   In <DATE>1918</DATE>, <PERSON>Sergeant Alvin C. York</PERSON> almost single-handedly killed 25
German soldiers and captured 132 in the <ORGANIZATION>Argonne Forest</ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION>France</LOCATION>.
   In <DATE>1934</DATE>, <PERSON>Bruno Hauptmann</PERSON> was indicted for murder in the death of
the infant son of <PERSON>Charles A. Lindbergh</PERSON>.
   In <DATE>1939</DATE>, the <ORGANIZATION>New York Yankees</ORGANIZATION> won the World Series in four games
straight, defeating the <LOCATION>Cincinnati</LOCATION> Reds, 7-4.
   In <DATE>1944</DATE>, ``The Adventures of Ozzie and Harriet'' made its debut
on <ORGANIZATION>CBS</ORGANIZATION> radio, an event that coincided with <PERSON>Ozzie</PERSON> and <PERSON>Harriet
Nelson</PERSON>'s ninth wedding anniversary.
   In <DATE>1945</DATE>, President <PERSON>Truman</PERSON> announced that the secret of the
atomic bomb would be shared only with <LOCATION>Britain</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>Canada</LOCATION>.
   In <DATE>1956</DATE>, <PERSON>Don Larsen</PERSON> pitched the only perfect game ever in a
World Series as the <ORGANIZATION>New York Yankees</ORGANIZATION> beat the <ORGANIZATION>Brooklyn Dodgers</ORGANIZATION>, 2-0.
   In <DATE>1957</DATE>, the <ORGANIZATION>Brooklyn Baseball Club</ORGANIZATION> announced it was accepting
an offer to move the <ORGANIZATION>Dodgers</ORGANIZATION> from <LOCATION>New York</LOCATION> to <LOCATION>Los Angeles</LOCATION>.
   In <DATE>1970</DATE>, exiled Soviet author <PERSON>Alexander I. Solzhenitsyn</PERSON> was
awarded the Nobel Prize for literature.
   In <DATE>1981</DATE>, at the <ORGANIZATION>White House</ORGANIZATION>, President <PERSON>Reagan</PERSON> greeted
predecessors <PERSON>Jimmy Carter</PERSON>, <PERSON>Gerald R. Ford</PERSON> and <PERSON>Richard M. Nixon</PERSON>
before sending them off to <LOCATION>Egypt</LOCATION> for the funeral of Anwar Sadat.
   In <DATE>1982</DATE>, the government of <LOCATION>Poland</LOCATION> banned all labor
organizations, including Solidarity.
   Ten years ago: Pope <PERSON>John Paul II</PERSON> returned to <LOCATION>Rome</LOCATION>, having
wrapped up a nine-day journey to <LOCATION>Ireland</LOCATION> and the <LOCATION>United States</LOCATION>.
   Five years ago: In an address to the <ORGANIZATION>U.N. General Assembly</ORGANIZATION>, the
president of <ORGANIZATION>El Salvador</ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON>Jose Napoleon Duarte</PERSON> unexpectedly offered
to hold peace talks with leftist guerrillas.
   One year ago: Pope <PERSON>John Paul II</PERSON> journeyed to eastern <LOCATION>France</LOCATION>,
where he addressed the Council of <LOCATION>Europe</LOCATION> and the <ORGANIZATION>European Court of
Human Rights</ORGANIZATION>.
   Today's Birthdays: Senator <PERSON>Spark Matsunaga</PERSON>, <LOCATION>D-Hawaii</LOCATION>, is 73.
Entertainment reporter <PERSON>Rona Barrett</PERSON> is 53. Actor <PERSON>David Carradine</PERSON> is
49. Reverend <PERSON>Jesse Jackson</PERSON> is 48. Comedian-actor <ORGANIZATION>Chevy Chase</ORGANIZATION> is 46.
Rock singer <PERSON>Johnny Ramone</PERSON> is 38. Actress <PERSON>Stephanie Zimbalist</PERSON> is 33.
   Thought for Today: ``I have always noticed that deeply and truly
religious persons are fond of a joke, and I am suspicious of those
who aren't.'' _ <PERSON>Alfred North Whitehead</PERSON>, English philosopher and
mathematician (1861-1947).
</TEXT>
